erties as viscosity, sound velocity at low frequency, Joule-Thomson coefficient, self-diffusion, and
PVT data. The value of 50. 51 was obtained by averaging,with appropriate weights, the values of
bo obtained from the above-mentioned experimental data.
The dimensionless representation has been accomplished for certain properties by expres¬
sing them relative to the value at standard conditions (0°C and 1 atmosphere). Thus, the density
is expressed as /° IfiQ, the sound velocity at low frequency as a/aq, the thermal conductivity as
k/kQ, and the viscosity as ij M q. The reference values /®o» ^0' ^ 0 were computed on the
basis of the Lennard-Jones intermolecular potential, whose force constants were evaluated in the
manner outlined above. The value kQ was determined from an equation based on an empirical
fit of the experimental data. Values for these quantities are given in various units in table 3-b.
The agreement of ^ q and kQ with the experimental data is shown in figures 3b and 3f. It can be
seen from figure 3e that the average departure of the experimental data at standard conditions
from the adopted value of 7) q is about 1 percent. The value of 307. 88 m/sec for aq is in agree¬
ment with the value 307. 8 m/sec cited in the International Critical Tables [36] and is further cor¬
roborated by the very recent determination by Greenspan of the National Bureau of Standards [37]
who reports a provisional value 307. 86 m/sec.
The viscosity was computed on the basis of the Lennard-Jones 6-12 intermolecular potential
with the same force constants as were used for the thermodynamic properties (see summary
