The ideal-gas thermodynamic properties for argon (table 3-12) are quite reliable, since the
atomic weight and the fundamental constants are the only source of uncertainty. The uncertainty
in the real-gas properties, is, therefore, due almost entirely to the uncertainty in the pressure
correction, that is, to the uncertainty in the virial coefficients and their derivatives. At high
temperatures and moderate pressures, where the gas imperfection is small, the thermodynamic
properties should be reliable as tabulated. Outside this region,the pressure correction for
entropy (table 3-5) and enthalpy (table 3-4) depends on the first derivative of the virial coefficients.
